The function relies on the `cleanup_op` member of the `pcap_t` structure. This `cleanup_op` is a function pointer that is initialized by the `pcap_open_*` functions. This `cleanup_op` is responsible for releasing any resources specific to the opened capture handle (e.g., closing file descriptors, freeing internal buffers). If `p` is not a valid `pcap_t` structure obtained from a `pcap_open_*` call, the `p->cleanup_op(p)` call will likely result in a segmentation fault or other undefined behavior due to accessing invalid memory or calling an uninitialized or incorrect function pointer.

Furthermore, `pcap_close` itself calls `free(p)`. This implies that the `pcap_t` structure passed to `pcap_close` is expected to have been allocated dynamically (likely by the `pcap_open_*` functions). Attempting to pass a `pcap_t` that was not dynamically allocated or is not managed by libpcap for closure will lead to a double-free or freeing invalid memory, causing crashes.

